segments.text: And they say that the most difficult problem on Kennedy's desk was, where shall the next cyclotron go?
Well, you know what happened in November of 63 in Dallas?
And Mr. Johnson became president as a consequence of that.
I recall at that time reading an article in the journal Science.
I've forgotten the author.
I want to say David.
It escapes me.
It was entitled, When Pure Science Meets Pure Politics.
And it was telling the story of
The machinations going on about where shall the next cyclotron go?
Well, Earl Rudder's association with Lyndon Johnson was clearly far and away the thing that turned that tide and got the cyclotron allocated to Texas A&M University.
Okay, but your question had to do with women and minorities.
Let's stay with that just a second.
Can you think of any other Rudder-Johnson relationships that brought some special blessing to A&M?
Not quickly offhand, no, Haskell.
But that cyclotron was a big one.
Let's see, then while we're on new programs, how did chemistry and economics come to be highlighted for great strengthening?
And I think chemistry came to be selected as a spotlight center because of the Welch Foundation and W.T.
Doherty's interest in chemistry.
Economics became selected as a program to be taken to national visibility.
I think mainly because of its already established recognition across the country as a good solid source of masters people who are quite capable at the doctoral level.
Al Chalk, head of the department, insisted upon all things on good teaching, outstanding teaching,
and selective recruitment of top students for the economics department.
And the young people that graduated with a degree in economics who wanted to go on and do graduate work were sought after, in fact, by the graduate schools across the country.
At that time, we did not have a doctorate in economics ourselves, and that didn't come until after Mel Greenhut got here.
Now, was that after liberal arts was split away from education, or was that under your days?
Did you hire Greenhut or was that later?
Yeah, I hired Greenhut.
I say I hired.
Al Chalk selected him, brought him in.
We employed him, yes.
And Greenhut immediately, on the good solid base in economics that he found, immediately
designated that this department's strength at the doctoral level shall be built toward econometrics, quantitative economics.
He said that's clearly the way the discipline is going and that he intended to recruit top people who were of that ilk.
Green Hut came from Florida, as I recall.
Florida State.
Florida State.
Florida State, okay.
Let's see.
Do you remember any pioneer women, outstanding female students that were precedent makers or setters?
No, I don't, Haskell.
Or any black student leaders before Fred McClure.
I don't know.
No, he was the top one then and in my mind is still now.
I agree.
Go back and trace, if you can, when Arts and Sciences was broken up and weren't there a number of steps going from Arts and Sciences to the five different colleges there?
that exists now.
By a number of steps you mean the procedural mechanism by which colleges are separated and established?
No, it didn't go from arts and sciences all at once, did it, to education, business?
Oh no, oh no.
Well, that's what I...
The first
change in organization was a separation of science and the others.
And the others came to be called the liberal arts.
And that took place late spring of 1965.
Let's see.
Oh, yes.
In 1965, the spring enrollment data, spring semester enrollment for 1965.
Oh, I see what I've done.

showed that the College of Arts and Sciences had become for the first time the largest college at the university, not only in terms of semester credit hours produced and size of faculty, but in numbers of students registered for degree purposes in that college.
Larger than engineering?
My God.
Larger than agriculture?
It can't be.
And of course, vet medicine was a small enrollment.
Boy, I think that was a catalyst which quickly brought the division of science from the liberal arts.
Plus one other feature.
By that time, I had an associate dean in science.
He had come from Rice University, was a distinguished scientist in the field of cryogenics, low temperature physics, whose name was Charles Squire.
Charles was a leading researcher supported by Welch funds.
And this again, I think, was the influence of W.T.
You need a scientist up there to help dean the sciences.
So I was advised one day that I needed an associate dean in science, and that come go with me.
This is President Rutter.
Let's go down to Rice and visit a guy in his laboratory and see what you think of him."
President Rudder and I took a trip to Rice, did spend a couple of hours in Charles Squire's laboratory, got acquainted with him, very interesting.
He came back, Frank, what would you think about having him as an associate dean for science?
Fine, okay, good.
No need to get rattled over such an item.
At the same time, there had been selected a new vice president for research at about this time,
One, Dr. Andrew Suttles.
And he had come from a commercial laboratory, I want to say one of the petrochemical people's laboratories, I've forgotten which, Exxon or Texaco or somebody like that.
Who identified him, do you know?
I'm sure it was W.T.
Daugherty, without any question.
and Earl, you need a vice president for research.
Maybe not in that language, but he was selected for that position.
Well, the coming of, I think they had been selected by this time, but by,
It was clear that science wanted to bask in its own sunlight and didn't want to be burdened with association with the liberal arts.
Think how much faster we can grow and what greater things we can do in science if we have our own identity, etc.
When the enrollment figures in the spring of
65 came in, that was a clincher.
Let's divide science out of liberal arts, out of arts and sciences, and that way they will no longer be the largest college on campus.
That's my conjecture, Haskell.
No one ever told me that, but it was relatively
Maybe it was just coincidence, happened at the same time, but I thought it had some effect.

let's see your question then after science uh... was created after science and liberal arts were divided then geosciences quickly followed the following year and the creation of a college of geoscience and that made sense mainly because of oceanography and meteorology which were in science

Had the largest sum of research going on in the university anywhere, I think at one time, and I'm not sure just when the date was, but at one time, the research volume in dollars going on in the Department of Oceanography and Meteorology, the aggregate was larger than all other research done on the campus.
And that brought also geology, what we now call geology and geophysics.
Geology and geophysics out of engineering.
And geography out of liberal arts.
And oceanography and meteorology well out of science.
Now then, at that time, science was so much on the move
And resources were being allocated to science that even A&M wasn't accustomed to.
President Rutter wanted members of the National Academy of Science to give our program better visibility.
We didn't have any at the time.

with the opportunity to employ a college, a dean of science, and a dean of geosciences the following year, he dedicated himself to a recruitment program that would be beamed at members of the academy.
And that's when Zener came aboard and Bowers from Chicago and from Pittsburgh.
Both top flight guys.
At this time then, what was left with the College of Liberal Arts, business and education, were they still called departments?
No, education was a department, but business was
and had always been a division.
Business administration was next to be separated out as a college.
And I forget the year.
It was after 65 and after, I want to say after 66, probably either 67 or eight.
And next, education was separated out.
I had an offer from the University of Texas in the fall of 1968 to return over there as a fully tenured, full professor and head of department

of the department from which i'd gotten my degree and uh norman hackerman then president of ut called earl rutter and said earl we want to see if we can get frank hubert over here to do this job for us earl called me over and said frank i know they're talking with you
I just want to ask you one thing, and that is, if you will, before you make a final decision on this, come sit down and talk with me.
I went over.
The job was offered to me firm, with tenure, the professorship, et cetera, and a salary that exceeded my dean's salary at A&M.
I went back and talked to Mary Julia, and we were uncertain as to what we wanted to do, really uncertain.
I was torn between the two.
Austin is so attractive, as is the University of Texas.
got an appointment with President Rutter, went in and sat down with him and told him the details.
And he said, well, Frank, if you want to return to education, isn't it time that we created a college of education here?
We'll create a college of education here and you can dean it if you want to.
I said, well, that's an inviting idea.
He says, well, I'll tell you what you do.
Bring me a short summary of what we need to do, the changes we need to make, and what it'll cost us to get a college of education going started.
Well, that evening, I went home.
sat down at my desk, wrote out a two-page summary of the organizational nature and the additional personnel required and what it would cost, and the identity of the departments.
Took it back in the next day.
He said, I'm going to call the members of the Executive Committee of the Regents.
and place this before them and see if we can't get quick action on it.
He did, and within another day, he called me in and said, Frank, the deanship of the new College of Education is yours if you want it.
And he says, we'll equal the salary that they offered you at UT.
I took that home to Mary Julian.
We agreed to accept it and did.
I don't know how it happened, but that was very early in 69.
President Rudder said, write the coordinating board proposal for the new college, as I had done for liberal arts and participated in the others.
He said, we'll get it moving.
I had it on his desk by the end of the week, the proposal for the new college and its organization and so forth.
Ordinarily, a proposal for a new college would usually take anywhere from 12 months to 18, minimum.
for it to go through all of the spots on the obstacle course.
But this one, it just seemed to set records.
It hit the calendar exactly right all along the way.
And by that following September, nine months later, we were authorized as a college with degrees, et cetera, et cetera, et cetera.
Including the doctoral?
Pardon?
Including the doctoral degrees?
No.
Oh, not yet.
We had to submit them separately to Haskell.
And we did so later on.
Then business... Business had already gone.
Education was the last to go.
Right.
How was John Pearson selected as the Dean of Business?
I did a search, got recommendations from a number of places.
Let me see.
I have forgotten where John Pearson's name came from.
I think he was at North Texas.
He was at North Texas.
I'm aware of that.
But I don't recall how his name got into focus.
I didn't know him or know of him, but it was recommended to my office.
From whom?
By whom?
Oh, my.
Nonetheless, he turned out to be the guy and was finally selected as dean of that new college.
I also had invited to participate in that selection a champ whom I had met in Wilmington, Delaware, while on a two-day visit to the EI DuPont, the Nemours Company.
with a group of other people from the soft sciences who was then associate dean of business at Notre Dame, a sparkling fellow.
But he turned the opportunity down.
He said, I've got too much ahead of me here.
Pearson was ultimately selected to become dean, and I don't recall where his name came from.
Fooey.
Okay.
Right.
As you then created the college, how did you identify the key people to take over the various units in the College of Education and your staff?
Well, in the College of Education, it was relatively easy.
The year before the College of Education was authorized, we had a vacancy in the headship of the Department of Education.
This is fall of 68.
Paul Henseling had a voice problem.
Difficulty in talking and being understood.
He asked to be
I returned to a professorship.
It was late in the summer of 68.
I did not want to conduct a search for a new department head at that late date, so I took it upon myself to occupy the two positions.
during that year, 68, 69, dean of liberal arts and head of the Department of Education.
I hope your transcriber will be aware that these costs are necessary, and I apologize
to her or him for it.
Now, as head of the Department of Education, I got a firsthand acquaintance with the people in education in their various fields and made the selections for their appointments on that basis.
I've heard also that the interim department head
sometimes wrote recommendations that the dean turned down during that period.
Yes.
Really.
I felt it obligatory as head of the department to make requests which I thought were justified, and I did.
And when I reviewed them from the dean's office, I looked at them in terms of the overall breadth and scope of the college at that time, and I said,
Yes, they need it, but we don't have the funds for it, and so forth.
Now, so we got off.
Well, we had some good people to start with.
Glenn Johnson, doctorate from Teachers College, Columbia.
Who was first head of Ed administration?
Les Richardson?
I don't know.
Finally got Hal Hawkins, doctorate from Harvard.
Ed Psychology, Art Roach, doctorate from Notre Dame.
Jim Boone from here at A&M, and his doctorate was here at A&M, I believe.
But we had some good people to start out with, and they were hard workers.
As this is being finished, we now know that Mr. Rutter's health was declining.
When did you become aware, you think, as you look back, that Mr. Rutter's health was being impaired?
I don't recall specifically Haskell, a specific moment in time.
But do you remember sometimes being with him, realizing that his energy wasn't what it had been?
I think so, and it showed up at the executive committee meetings more than any place else.
He just didn't have the go and punch that he had.
And...
But he was keeping pace with the fast-moving events on campus, sometimes not only keeping up with them, but out there in front pulling them along.
He was also traveling.
You can't imagine the travels that he took.
I think he responded to every request made of him to make a speech anywhere.
Whatever the subject so long as it related to Texas A&M University.
Who were his key contacts in Austin and Washington?
The individuals that he knew best that really helped A&M a lot.
Tiger Teague in Washington, plus later LBJ himself.
Let's see.
John Connolly?
Yes, John Connolly.
Bill Moore, of course, although he was not in Austin, he was of Austin in a way.
Who was Speaker of the House at that time?
I don't know.
I don't recall either, but I think that was a good relationship for A&M.
And was Heatley one of Mr. Rutter's close contacts?
I don't recall.
As chairman of whatever it was, Ways and Means or Appropriations?
I don't think he was a great friend, as I recall.
And Senator Aiken?
I don't know.
I just don't know about Aiken.
During the Rutter years, who was the key A&M person to work with the coordinating board?
His vice president, I think.
Right, the chief, what we now call the provost, vice president of academic affairs.
Yes.
When you first, do you recall any event, any circumstance under which you heard Mr. Rutter had been hospitalized?
How did you all hear about it?
How did you all know that he was seriously ill?
I don't recall when or how that message came.
It's not clear in my memory when it came.
I remember hearing that after he was hospitalized, shortly after he was hospitalized, he was rushed to surgery.
And he had to be taken in a subterranean channel from one building to another.
And it was quite a group there moving along with him.
This was in Houston.
This is in Houston, yes.
Let's see.
His surgeon was, who's the guy?
It wasn't DeBakey.
It was, do you recall?
The other top guy.
There are two down there.
The name is easy to recall.
Denton Cooley.
I think he did the surgery.
It was just a shock when we heard of his death.
An absolute shock.
Do you remember the memorial service?
Yes, very moving.
I remember his being laid in state in the rotunda of the administration building.
Ludeke was named interim.
the board began its search for a new president of the system and the university.
Called in, I think, each of the deans.
I know I was called to express my views about those that they were examining.
Really?
Oh, good.
Didn't know that.
How appropriate were their questions?
Very good questions.
Excellent questions.
Among the board members, who seemed to be the key movers and shakers at that point?
Haskell, hard to recall, I remember that Ford Allbritton was active in the search for the new president.
I also had heard prior to my going for the interview that Jack Williams was being considered.
And my comment to the board was, you need look no further.
If you can get this man to come back to Texas, you will have indeed pulled off a great coup for this university.
Do you know who it was that originally suggested his name to them?
No.
You?
Earl Rudder told Fort Albritton and John Lindsay a year and a half earlier in response to their question,
Earl, God help us if it were to happen, but what should we do if anything ever happened to you?
Do you have somebody on site?
And Mr. Albritton said that Mr. Rutter said, no, I don't, and it's my fault.
I ought to, but I don't.
Well, what do we do if?
Well, if you do...
And he said that this was an hour or two later that he said, I've been thinking about it since then.
And you go up there because his coordinating board experience, his knowledge of Texas, and his experience at Clemson and with the Southern Association has been so extensive.
And Ford said, well, if that's what Earl thought, the board was very... Do you...
Each of the deans were called in.
Do you remember anybody else that they...
I don't know that...
I didn't hear from other deans that they were called in.
I'm assuming that they were, Haskell.
But I don't know of anyone else who might have been endorsed by...
A dean or other deans.
As far as you know, did Dr. Williams come to the campus for a pre-selection interview visit?
That I do not know.
I don't think he did.
I don't know.
How did you learn that he had been selected?
I think by the media.
And what was the first impression that you and others had of
Dr. Williams as president?
Great excitement.
Just extremely happy that he would be willing to come to A&M and take the leadership role here that he did.
Give some examples of some of his early decisions, early successes.
Haskell, it's hard to say.
He was so active on so many fronts.
I know that during the interim period with Ludeke there, Lude began
involving students more in some of the basic exercises and decisions than had ever been done before.
When President Williams came, he picked that up and took it on to higher levels.
President Williams also sought
advice from faculty groups and individuals at an unprecedented pace, I think.
Can you think of any skills that a university CEO needed that Jack Williams didn't have?
He was a good speaker.
good experience, energetic, student, faculty, sensitive, and so forth?
He had it all, Haskell.
Click that off just a minute.
Okay.
One of Dr. Williams' key appointments was John Calhoun as vice president.
Yes.
Describe him as the chief academic officer and his relationship with you and your dean colleagues.
Yeah.
I didn't know John very well prior to his appointment as the academic vice president.
After he was appointed, there was no special relationship between the two of us.
I responded in the usual way to all of the
normal request for the flow of information up to that office.
I remember one occasion when Dr. Calhoun, I think, how to say this,

challenged a decision i had made in a way it was a student matter and a young lady in the college of liberal arts had come to me asking if she could take 21 hours of work in a single semester i looked at her record and i said no

she asked if there was someone else she could see about this and i said yes if you want to question my decision you can go see the vice president for academic matters she did john called me over and i think john was tempted to support the young lady i said john i just can't go with it and he sustained me but i have the feeling that
If it had been himself alone, he would have ruled otherwise.
That may have been an error on my part.
That's the only time I remember a question about a decision I had made.
Other than that, I think our relationships were quite friendly all along the way, Haskell.
The enrollment was zooming upward because Dr. Williams had made it a condition of his acceptance of the offer that an existing dormitory be identified for women in January of 1971.
He begins in the fall of 70.
And there had been no housing on campus for women.
How did that zoom in enrollment, how did that affect you and your colleagues?
Well, in the College of Education, of course, it was a great boon.
The women's opportunity for positions other than in teaching had not yet developed to the point where they were a strong magnet.
for women to go to engineering, to go to business especially, and to other colleges.
If you were a woman, you trained to be a teacher.
And as a consequence, the College of Education
experienced a big, big increase in enrollment very rapidly, quickly.
Do you remember any incidents that the increase in women caused?
I don't remember any problems.
The only problem was space.
Right, for classes and faculty and staff, but I don't remember any student resentment or antagonism.
No, no.
Let's see.
Dr. Williams then was the president of the system and of the institution as Mr. Rutter had been.
Yes.
What were the benefits or the handicaps of that arrangement?
Well, the handicaps were one of time, I think.
The demands upon the president of the university are so extensive.
And the demands upon the president, or now chancellor of the system, are again extensive.
That to me, it's difficult to see how one person can live through the two jobs concurrently.
I think that's one thing that got Earl Rutter.
It may have contributed some to Jack Williams.
But as you may know, a legislative committee in 1948 visited A&M as a result of a student uprising.
And they had marched on the president's home.
In effect, they wanted more attention for student matters.
Well, Haskell legislature appointed a committee to come investigate it.

Incidentally on that committee was a brother-in-law of mine at that time a senator from Dallas Fred Harris, oh, yes, okay a Baylor graduate now a Part of that committee's report said clearly you should separate the two positions name a chancellor and a president and
And proceed accordingly.
I don't know when that was abandoned.
When Dr. Harrington retired?
Yes.
And I think he retired a little earlier than he wanted to.
Oh, yes, yes.
And Mr. Rutter acquired both?
Both positions, yeah.
Okay.
Because I have heard a myth, you might have been in the room,

I've heard a myth that at some key committee meeting, I don't know whether it was Dean's or not, Mr. Rutter came back from some session somewhere and came into the room and closed the door and said, I won.
That he and Harrington had been going toe-to-toe.
It had been a test of strength, and he supposedly had won.
Hadn't heard about that.
Then I heard Dr. Harrington say,
say, post-retirement a couple of times, I heard him say, well, I got fired twice.
I got fired as president and as chancellor.
